Management_actions: 8 - 10 armyworm larvae per m2 (damage to leaf tissue - winter and early spring)

Management_actions: 1 - 3 larvae per m2  (crop ripening – head lopping risk)
Potentil_impacts: Depletion of green material that can lead to head lopping
Potentil_impacts_ext_info: Barley is susceptible to damage if mature caterpillars are present in spring due feeding behaviour that can cause head lopping. Management_actions: 0.2 larvae/10 sweeps (excluding very small larvae < 3 mm)
Potentil_impacts: Yield loss to developing pods / premium downgrade / partial seed damage
Potentil_impacts_ext_info: Younger larvae can enter emerging pods and damage developing seed while larger caterpillars may devour the entire pod contents. While all larval stages can cause feeding damage, the last two larval stages account for over 90% of native budworm grain consumption. Larger seeded pulses line field pea are more susceptible to a premium downgrade due to nibbled grain from native budworm feeding causing partial seed damage.

Larger seeded pulses line field pea are more susceptible to a premium downgrade due to nibbled grain from native budworm feeding causing partial seed damage.

Susceptible_crop_stage_of_interest: Younger crop stages: sowing to tillering
Management_actions: 8 - 10 armyworm larvae per m2 (damage to leaf tissue - winter and early spring)
Potentil_impacts: Damage to leaf tissue
Potentil_impacts_ext_info: This pest risk period might result in foliage loss, which could be severe if densities are well above threshold. However, cereal head loss is less likely.

Management_actions: 1 - 3 larvae per m2  (crop ripening – head lopping risk)
Potentil_impacts: Depletion of green material that can lead to head lopping
Potentil_impacts_ext_info: Barley is susceptible to damage if mature caterpillars are present in spring due feeding behaviour that can cause head lopping. Barley has a relatively thin stem, making it easier for larvae to chew through in comparison to a plant like wheat. Depletion of green material can lead to head lopping behaviour.
